http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The ultimate goal of a PE curriculum is to enable students to move proficiently and enable them to participate in health enhancing activities throughout their lifetime. To insure that students attain these standards and capabilities, they must have the opportunity to frequently participate in a wide variety of activities that develop fitness and movement proficiency.
Reading for Literacy in PE

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The following standards offer a focus for instruction each year and help ensure that students gain adequate exposure to a range of texts and tasks. Rigor is also infused through the requirement that students read increasingly complex texts through the grades. Students advancing through the grades are expected to meet each year's grade-specific standards and retain or further develop skills and understandings mastered in preceding grades.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The following standards offer a focus for instruction to help ensure that students gain adequate mastery of a range of skills and applications. Each year in their writing, students should demonstrate increasing sophistication in all aspects of language use, from vocabulary and syntax to the development and organization of ideas, and they should address increasingly demanding content and sources. Students advancing through the grades are expected to meet each year's grade-specific standards and retain or further develop skills and understandings mastered in preceding grades.

Motor Skills and Movement Patterns: Students demonstrate competency in motor skills and movement patterns needed to perform a variety of physical activities.
Perform basic (fundamental) locomotor skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate walk, run, leap, jump, hop, gallop, slide, and skip in skill development practice/activities (e.g., run when you hear the color of your eyes; jump over a line on the floor; leap over a pillow).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform basic nonlocomotor skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate balance on stable and unstable objects (e.g., walk on a rope on the floor, a balance board, on top of tires) and/or demonstrate weight transfer/tumbling skills (e.g., log roll, egg roll, forward roll).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform basic manipulative skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate eye-hand and eye-foot coordination skills (e.g., throw a ball above head, hit a balloon with hands, strike a balloon with a racquet, bounce a ball, kick a stationary ball).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform basic movements in a rhythmic manner.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform locomotor skills to a specific rhythm (e.g., walk to the rhythm as the teacher gives/calls directions for a simple circle dance; walk to drum beat; jump over a stationary rope on the floor while counting in a rhythm).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform locomotor skills with developmentally appropriate challenges to reinforce learning of basic movements.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate locomotor movements in basic combinations during skill development practice, activities, and games (e.g., jump on a pattern of poly spots; run and leap over obstacles; walk or run on an outdoor fitness trail; walk, skip to the words in a poem).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform nonlocomotor skills with developmentally appropriate challenges to reinforce learning fundamental movements.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate static balances (e.g., one leg balance, two hands and one foot balance) and dynamic balance on stable and unstable objects (e.g., walk backwards on a balance board, walk forward on a balance board and step over objects, walk on a pattern of stepping stones, jump on a pattern of poly spots).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform manipulative skills with developmentally appropriate challenges to reinforce learning fundamental movements.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate eye-hand and eye-foot coordination in skill development practice/activities and physical fitness activities/games (e.g., with a baseball bat hit a ball off a tee; consecutively catch self-tossed beach ball; kick a ball with power; bounce or dribble a ball while kneeling; jump a stationary rope on the floor and progress to a self-turned rope).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform fundamental rhythmic skills alone, with a partner, or in a group.
Perform locomotor skills proficiently and in combinations with developmentally appropriate challenges.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate locomotor moving in basic combinations in skill development practice/activities and physical fitness activities/games (e.g., run and leap over a series of obstacles, hop and jump a pattern on a floor ladder, walk and skip in a dance).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform stability skills proficiently and in combinations, with developmentally appropriate challenges.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate static balance and dynamic balance in combinations on stable and unstable objects (e.g., walk on a balance board on an incline, travel over tires and carry an object extended above head, skip on a balance board, perform a one leg pose on a stepping stone); weight transfer/tumbling skills (e.g., tumbling routine with four skills).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform manipulative skills proficiently with developmentally appropriate challenges.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate eye-hand and eye-foot coordination skills in physical fitness activities/games (e.g., develop coordination and accuracy in the overhand throw to a target with increasing distances; pass a beach ball over a 5 - 6 foot high net with the overhand technique; develop new footwork and skills for jumping rope: skier, one foot, turn the rope backwards).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform fundamental rhythmic skills proficiently alone, with a partner or in a group.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform a dance with challenging steps (e.g., dos-a-dos and sashay with a partner in circle and line dances); demonstrate a consistent rhythm while jumping rope, (e.g., achieve 15 or more consecutive jumps while jumping to music).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform locomotor and manipulative combined skills with developmentally appropriate challenges.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate motor skill combinations in skill development practice/activities and physical fitness activities/games (e.g., while bouncing a ball, walk/run to pick up items from the floor and take to a collection box; dribble and pass the ball to a teammate in an indoor soccer leadup game; while walking, toss and catch a beanbag on a racquet or paddle).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate mature fundamental locomotor and manipulative movement skills with variations.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate variations of jumping (e.g., vertical, horizontal) and throwing a ball (e.g., two hands, underhand, sidearm).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate different fundamental movement skills to form increasingly complex skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Combine bouncing (dribbling) a ball while running at different speeds, using the inside and outside of the feet, and passing accurately to a teammate.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Utilize manipulative equipment combined with movement skills to perform specific sport skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Use an appropriate size bat and demonstrate striking a ball that is tossed by a partner; use a short handled paddle or racquet to strike a moving object (e.g., ball, shuttlecock/birdie, etc.); manipulate tininkling sticks in a rhythmic manner in a dance.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate movement skills and patterns following specific rhythms.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform a ball routine consisting of a bounce, pass and catch with a partner in rhythm to the music.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate mature movement patterns in locomotor, nonlocomotor, and manipulative skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate a mature (proficient) hop (e.g., nonsupport leg flexed 90o, nonsupport thigh lifts with vertical thrust of support foot, greater body lean, rhythmical action of nonsupport leg, arms move together in rhythmical lifting as support foot leaves ground).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Practice combinations of movement skills for specific sports.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform a catch, dribble, and pass with a ball to a moving partner.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate complex patterns of movement.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Design and demonstrate a movement routine using a series of related movements (e.g., tumbling routine, aerobic dance).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate movement skills and patterns following specific rhythms.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform a jump rope routine with a partner consisting of a variety of skills in rhythm to music (e.g., skier, criss-cross, side and front straddle); execute an aerobic dance routine in rhythm to music.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate the ability to integrate locomotor and nonlocomotor movements in more complex skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate mature (proficient) movement patterns in increasingly challenging environments (e.g., obstacle course, stunts and tumbling routine).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Develop the ability to manipulate objects with the skills necessary to participate in games and leadup activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Engage in leadup activities (mini-game applying several skills) requiring manipulative skills (e.g., small-sided soccer game with no goalies; three versus three floor hockey or basketball).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate the ability to perform more complex rhythmic skills alone and with a partner.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform rhythmic movement sequences with music (e.g., cooperative jump rope routine with a partner, basketball dribbling routine, line dance).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate more advanced forms in locomotor, nonlocomotor, and manipulative skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Dribble a basketball around objects using both left and right hands with greater accuracy and control.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate basic competency in more specialized movement skills related to specific physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Design and perform a 60 second dance sequence using combinations of locomotor and nonlocomotor skills with changes of direction, force, and level.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate a movement sequence in a physical activity or game.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Move back from the net, when playing a game of pickleball, allow the ball to bounce and return it over the net with an underhand movement.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate more complex combinations of movement forms in various sport and rhythmic activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform the schottische step in a folk dance, moves in a hip hop dance, or a right and left hand star in a square dance.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Combine and refine fundamental techniques in games and sports and work towards achieving competence in increasingly complex physical activity contexts.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in several different physical activities such as golf, gymnastics, inline skating, martial arts, tennis, swimming, and/or small sided team sports.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Create rhythmic movement patterns demonstrating an understanding of steady beat, tempo, and phrasing of music to maintain and improve fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform movements and routines in activities such as dance, aerobics, and jump rope.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Movement Concepts: Students demonstrate an understanding of movement concepts, principles, strategies, and tactics as they apply to the learning and performance of physical activities.
Demonstrate basic (fundamental) movement vocabulary and cue words for learning skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recognize movements and cues (e.g., gallop cue: leader leg; forward roll cue: be small and roll like a ball; kick a ball cue: toe down).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate variations in moving with spatial, directional, and temporal awareness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Move in various directions (forward, backward, sideward), at various levels (high, low), in various patterns (straight, curved), and at various speeds (fast, slow) in skill development activities (e.g., walk on a curved rope on the floor; stretch high, low level for a crab walk; run fast in a tag game).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and demonstrate basic principles for learning basic movement skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Verbally identify and practice the basic principles for balance (e.g., arms extended for walking on a balance board), basic footwork skills (e.g., soccer ball dribble with soft taps of feet), and catching a ball (e.g., reach out with hands).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate fundamental movement vocabulary and cue words for learning skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recognize movements and cues (e.g., step forward on the opposite foot throwing cue: step with the other foot).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and demonstrate the basic principles of age appropriate locomotor, nonlocomotor and manipulative skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Verbally identify and practice the basic elements for bouncing (dribbling) a ball (e.g., keep ball below the waist, pads of fingers push the ball, dribble ball to the side).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate variations in moving with directional, spatial and temporal awareness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Move in various directions (e.g., forward, backward, sideward, left, right, up, down) at various levels (high, medium, low), in various patterns (straight, curved, zigzag), and at various speeds (fast, medium, slow) in skill development activities (e.g., walk sideward as bouncing the ball, crab walk backwards at a low level, or jump a zigzag poly spot pattern.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify major body parts, muscles and bones used to move and support the body.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Verbally and visually identify body parts, muscles and bones (e.g., head, arm, chest, lungs; heart, biceps, triceps; skull, ribs).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and demonstrate efficient movement with objects that present balance, change of direction and spatial awareness challenges.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Successfully navigate through an obstacle course (e.g., over and under hurdles, stepping stones, travel over tires, crawl through a tunnel, travel through a mat maze, jump down from a height, walk on a balance board carrying an object).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and begin to demonstrate techniques for efficient and safe movement.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate straight arms with a cartwheel; a landing with soft knees/slight flex when jumping down from a height; jumping on balls of the feet and keeping arms and hands at sides when jumping rope.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and apply the basic elements for efficient locomotor, nonlocomotor, stability, and manipulative skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Verbally identify and practice the basic elements for gallop (e.g., moving forward: step, together, step, together); cartwheel (e.g., straight arms and hand, hand, foot, foot); overhand throw to a target (e.g., opposite shoulder points to the target, elbow back, ball back, step and turn to face target, throw); jumping rope (e.g., jump softly on balls of feet, keep arms and hands at sides when turning the rope); jumping from a 1 to 3 foot height (e.g., balanced landing with soft knees/slight bend and arms extend out).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understand and demonstrate strategies for active games.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recognize and apply basic strategies in playing games (e.g., small-sided defense and offense skills in an indoor soccer leadup game played with four high density foam balls; fast running, dodging and agility skills in a tag game).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Develop selected academic concepts to integrate in fitness workouts and/or games.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Apply interdisciplinary connections while jumping rope by solving math problems or spelling words (e.g., jump the answer to a math problem: 5 + 8; spell words with warm-up exercises: day of the week, words from spelling lists, names of muscles; body, muscles, and bones quiz station in a physical fitness activity).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe various balance forms utilizing base of support concepts.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate stability awareness (e.g., lower center of gravity, wide base of support, number of balance points for more stability) as applied to stable bases of support (e.g., arabesque or scale, wrestler's bridge, tripod, bear walk, football stance).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe movement principles and apply mature movement patterns in various manipulative challenges.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify striking a ball (batting), juggling, and alternating toe touches as being skills that cross the midline; observe the performance of others (in class, on videotape) to detect performance errors in efficient movement.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe and demonstrate the use of force to move objects various distances.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice kicking a ball with ankle flexion, knee extension, and hip flexion producing light, medium, and hard force (power) to observe the distance the ball travels at each level of force.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe critical elements of correct movement pattern for fundamental movement skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe and demonstrate body positions for each of the parts of bouncing (dribbling) a ball (e.g., feet placed in narrow stride, slight forward trunk lean, ball held waist high, ball pushed toward ground with fingertips).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Apply the concept of practice to improve movement skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Work toward accurately passing a ball to a target using a chest pass.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Observe the performance of others to provide feedback to help improve motor skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Carefully observe another student (in class, on videotape) kicking a ball and complete a peer evaluation with a checklist or rubric.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize and describe critical elements of complex movement patterns.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe the use of specific body parts and summation of forces (e.g., arms back, knees bent, lower level) for increasing distance in the standing long jump.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify movement concepts used to refine movement skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe how timing and power improves performance of propelling a gymnasium-type bowling ball at the pins.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe and demonstrate critical elements of mature movement patterns.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe the movement of the arm and trunk in accurately throwing a ball overhand at a target.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Critique the performance of a partner by providing feedback to help improve skill.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Observe a classmate (in class, on videotape) kicking a ball at a target and complete a peer evaluation with checklist or rubric.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify basic concepts that apply to the movement and sport skills being practiced.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Observe a student throwing a softball different distances using varied trajectories (angles) and amounts of force.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain how practicing movement skills improve performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Maintain a log of practice attempts for throwing a disc at a target, comparing differences in successful throws from first attempts to last attempts.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe basic strategies for offense and defense in simple leadup games.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Mark (guard) another player who is dribbling a soccer ball and attempt to prevent a pass or shot; throw a pass to an open teammate who has eluded the defense in a small-sided football game (e.g., game played on a smaller field with fewer players to allow for more student participation).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Learn and apply principles necessary for skilled performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Throw a ball for distance using the most appropriate trajectory (angle).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize the open person concept in team sport activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice the skill of open-positioning during a game of disc golf and/or deliver a pass to an open teammate moving downfield through defenders to score a goal.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe and demonstrate the difference between being on offense and defense in various activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Move into proper position for receiving a serve in badminton and then quickly change to offense in anticipation of the return shot and/or move into proper position on the court to apply a person-to-person or zone defense in a basketball game and be able to quickly transition from defense to offense.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe variations of movement skills that occur in sport activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Break down the sport of softball by identifying the locomotor, nonlocomotor, and manipulative skills important in the game (e.g., underhand throw, overhand throw, catching).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explore basic physics principles (action-reaction, trajectory, levers, linear velocity) that are utilized in specific sport activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Draw a racquetball court and diagram expected ball rebound angles for a variety of game situations: practice hitting a racquetball against walls at different heights and force to explore the rebound angles; use various lengths of racquets to apply concepts of levers.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze an athlete's performance of a sport skill, using technology, and provide suggestions for improving the performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Observe a hurdler's unsuccessful attempt to clear a hurdle and describe what needs to be changed to make the attempt successful.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe strategies used in a net/wall game situation.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain at least two game tactics involved in playing badminton doubles (e.g., hitting deep into opponent's court [e.g., creating space], overlap with partner for court coverage).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Physical Activity: Students participate regularly in physical activity.
Show skills and knowledge acquired in physical education class during after school physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate willing participation in active play at recess, in unstructured play with friends and family, or in community recreation/sport leagues (e.g., teacher initiates conversation with students for informal assessment of after school physical activity participation).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Display enjoyment in participation in moderate to vigorous physical activity in physical education class and in after school time.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Express enthusiasm and enjoyment while being physically active (e.g., choose favorite games to play; willingly participate in learning new movement skills; choose to be active at recess).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Engage in health-related physical fitness activities or games during physical education class, recess, and/or or leisure time with one's family and friends.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in physical fitness activities/games, playground activities, swimming, walking, riding a bicycle, playing in the snow, and/or tennis.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Record participation in physical activities by type of activity and time.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Write and draw periodically in a student activity portfolio about the physical fitness activities/games and/or sport skills that one enjoys playing to be healthy.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate actively in all physical education classes and in unorganized or organized physical fitness and play opportunities during after school time.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Enter a game situation, skills practice, and/or family physical activity voluntarily (e.g., competition is minimal to encourage participation).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participates in and keeps a record of activities outside of physical education class that provide opportunities to demonstrate a healthy lifestyle.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Record participation time from a gymnastics, swimming, martial arts class, or other physical activities in a student activity portfolio (e.g., child-friendly designed weekly chart is provided for periodic activity recording).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Select and participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity in physical education class and during after school time.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Record participation in healthy lifestyle activities/sports while playing with friends and family, and attempt to learn challenging sport skills.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify healthy behaviors that represent a physically active lifestyle.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss quality nutrition and rest for one's body and how it compliments a physically active lifestyle (e.g., junk food versus fruits and vegetables; cola drinks versus water; lack of rest versus a minimum of 9-10 hours of sleep per night).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and demonstrate the physical, mental, social, and emotional benefits of participation in health-related physical fitness activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: List the benefits that result from participation in physical fitness activities (e.g., decreases heart disease, strengthens sport performance, increases mental alertness, improves attention and memory, improves self-esteem, decreases stress); and/or contrast excessive sedentary activities to a physically active lifestyle (e.g., TV, video games, screen time versus ice skating, swimming, hiking).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate regular participation in health-related physical fitness activities outside of class.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in family fitness activities or practice independently for a youth sport league two to three afternoons per week.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and participate in lifetime physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss why tennis, softball, swimming, golfing, hiking, and jogging learned in physical education class are considered lifetime physical activities that can be enjoyed in the community.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in health-enhancing physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Establish personal physical activity goals (e.g., independently practice five times a week for participation in a youth soccer league); log participation of after school physical activities in a student activity portfolio.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize the positive effects of participation in leisure time physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Awareness of mental benefits (e.g., alertness, focus) of physical activity participation; discuss emotional benefits (e.g., joy, acceptance, satisfaction) of being physically active in a game that is personally enjoyable.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and participate in activities that, when done consistently, can contribute to an active lifestyle.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: List activities that can increase cardiorespiratory endurance and/or muscular strength and endurance, as well as other components of health-related physical fitness, and participate in a chosen activity at least 5 days per week.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in activities, outside of school, that are health-enhancing and can be continued throughout a lifetime.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Report in a student activity portfolio the participation level in golfing, cycling, or walking with a parent during the weekend (e.g., played nine holes of golf while walking the course, cycling five miles, walking 20 blocks).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the elements of a healthy lifestyle.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Use the FITT (frequency, intensity, type, and time) principle to describe activities that would lead to an active lifestyle.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Select and participate in activities that will build a repertoire of lifetime physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify, describe and participate in individual and dual lifetime activities, as well as team sports that can be played in community leagues throughout life.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Select and participate in a new sport or physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a school or community sponsored youth activity (e.g., canoe and/or camping trip during school break).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choose health-enhancing physical activities for leisure time.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a game of tennis with a friend at the community courts as a preferred form of relaxation and/or recreation.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in a variety of activities based upon likes, dislikes, fitness needs, environment, and availability of resources.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in competitive or recreational swimming after school.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Locate and participate in new activities available in the community.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Learn and participate in a session of orienteering or disc golf.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Choose activities based upon skill level and individual physical needs.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in weight training activities to enhance the strength of specific muscles for need improvement.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Health-Enhancing Physical Fitness: Students achieve and maintain a health-enhancing level of physical fitness.
Demonstrate improved cardiorespiratory endurance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Engage in vigorous activity, progressing from short periods to longer periods of time (e.g., chasing and fleeing physical fitness activity/game, skill development activity, walk/run at one's individual pace at an outdoor fitness trail; playground fitness stations).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate improved muscular strength and endurance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Improve upper body and abdominal strength by engaging in specific exercises throughout the school year (e.g., shoulder touches, modified push-ups, v-sit, modified crunch).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate improved flexibility in three different joints.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate engagement in specific stretches to improve lower back flexion (e.g., seated and standing straddle stretches, seal stretch).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify the basic effects of physical activity on heart and lung function.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Observe and feel fast heart and breathing rates when engaged in skill development and physical fitness activities (e.g., feel a slow heart rate and observe a slow breathing rate before skill and fitness stations begin, after ten or more minutes feel and observe fast heart and breathing rates).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate how increasing the intensity of an activity will increase the heart rate.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe and monitor the difference in the heart rate during a five minute warm-up walk, run or stretching as compared to 20 minutes of motor skill development and physical fitness stations.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the basic effect of regular exercise on muscles.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Compare the scores from three exercise trials and draw conclusions (e.g., at the beginning of the school year, record the score achieved for a specific muscle group exercise; complete mid-year and final year-end trials).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform exercises for muscle groups that are strengthened by specific exercises.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify and perform the exercises which strengthen the abdominal muscles and those which strengthen the arm muscles (e.g., v-sit, modified crunch, shoulder touches, modified push-ups, crab walk, partner over and under push-ups).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in activities that increase cardiorespiratory endurance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate engagement in physical fitness activities and describe the effects of exercise on the heart and lungs (e.g., increased heart and breathing rates, increase in perspiration).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate stretches that will improve flexibility.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate standing straddle toe touch, splits, lunge, and seal stretches.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in an active physical education class to maintain age appropriate intensity and duration for improved physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in skill development activities and/or games for 20 minutes or more in each physical education class to maintain or improve cardiorespiratory endurance, muscle strength and endurance, and flexibility (e.g., partners take turns to run/walk a lap, with the non-runner choosing a skill development practice station, combined with 20 second periodic breaks for upper body and abdominal exercises and stretching; obstacle course designed with a variety of movement and physical fitness challenges).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in an active physical education class to maintain the intensity and duration for improved physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in skill development activities/games and physical fitness activities for 20 minutes or more to maintain or improve cardiorespiratory endurance, muscle strength and endurance, and flexibility (e.g., skill and fitness activities stations: eye-hand coordination skill development practice stations, rope jump station, flexibility station, muscle strength and endurance stations).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe what can happen to the body of a person who does not exercise and who consumes too much food.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Verbally describe how body composition is affected by sedentary activity and food consumption (e.g., class discussion of too much screen time, video games, over-eating and how these affect a healthy level of body fat and muscle).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Develop and describe the components of health-related physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a circuit training activity and follow with discussion to identify the components of health-related physical fitness (e.g., strong muscles, basic heart and lung function, flexibility, and body fat).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform and recognize the difference between high, medium, and low intensity activities for developing cardiorespiratory endurance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify walking as a low intensity activity, jogging as a medium intensity activity, and running as a high intensity activity for developing cardiorespiratory endurance (e.g., students feel their heart beats and observe their breathing rate after trying each of these levels of activity).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in self assessments and formal fitness assessments.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Evaluate personal fitness using the results of weekly fitness workouts and a standardized fitness test (e.g., refer to age/grade scores on a chart, determine levels of self improvement).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify strengths and areas needing improvement in personal fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Utilize a performance chart from a criterion-referenced assessment to determine if individual fitness level is within the healthy fitness zone (e.g., child-friendly designed weekly chart is provided for periodic activity recording).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Establish personal goals based upon results of fitness assessments.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Establish a goal to do daily flexibility (range of motion of a joint) exercises with the hamstring muscles (back of thigh) and lower back to improve test results; create a list of physical activities to participate in after school and/or weekends with goals for frequency and duration.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Define and develop the five components of health-related physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe cardiorespiratory endurance, muscular strength, muscular endurance, flexibility, and body composition and develop skills through a gymnastics circuit (e.g., tumbling skills stations, balance board skills stations, low parallel bars basic skills station, rings basic skills station, vault and take-off board basic skills station, flexibility stations, muscle strength and endurance stations).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe and demonstrate examples of the five components of health-related physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify and demonstrate an exercise to increase muscular strength of the upper arms (e.g., biceps curl, triceps extension) and/or an awareness of continuous movement in caloric expenditure to achieve healthy level of body composition.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in activities that enhance health-related physical fitness on a regular basis.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in daily aerobic workouts or active games/sports, in physical education class and/or at home, to develop cardio-respiratory endurance.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in self-assessments for physical fitness and meet the criterion for specific age groups.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Strive to achieve the healthy fitness zone standard for a criterion-referenced assessment of health-related physical fitness; use results of heart rate monitor or computer generated reports to reinforce fitness understanding.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Establish personal goals based upon results of fitness assessments.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: To improve pushup test result, establish a goal to do upper body strength exercises (e.g., partner tug of war, pushup hockey, pushup style Tic-Tac-Toe).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe exercises/activities that will improve each component of health-related physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: List specific stretches and activities that will improve flexibility of specific muscle groups (e.g., lower back, hamstrings, quadriceps).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in an activity program that is designed to improve health-related physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in an after school exercise program (e.g., fitness, yoga, walking) several days per week; join family and friends to walk/jog at a neighborhood park at least three times per week.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Establish personal goals to achieve an age appropriate fitness level in all components of health-related physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Using the results of a fitness pretest, demonstrate how to set personal fitness goals; using posttest results, determine if goals were achieved.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate a healthy level of cardiorespiratory endurance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in an active game for 30 minutes or more while wearing a pedometer and identify the number of steps range to achieve a healthy level for age/grade.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate age appropriate levels of muscular strength and muscular endurance for major muscle groups.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a developmentally appropriate exercise circuit designed to improve muscular strength and endurance.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate a healthy level of flexibility.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Create a warm-up routine to target areas of the body on which the student needs to improve flexibility; practice slow martial arts movements.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate a healthy level of body composition.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Measure body fat and calculate body mass index (BMI) to determine if within healthy fitness zone of criterion-referenced fitness assessment.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Increase the intensity and duration of an activity while performing locomotor skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Keep a record of the heart rate after participation in a physical activity and evaluate whether the exercise intensity of the activity was sufficient to produce a target heart rate

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Develop personal goals for each of the health-related physical fitness components.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Set a goal to achieve a healthy fitness level for upper body strength (e.g., pull ups, push-ups) or for cardio-respiratory endurance (e.g.,10,000 steps daily using a pedometer).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Measure personal fitness levels in each of the health-related physical fitness components in relation to age.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a fitness test; record and review the results.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Utilize self-assessment of physical fitness to identify strengths and weaknesses and use this information to develop a personal fitness program.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Develop a personal physical fitness program that addresses all components of health-related fitness (e.g., use the FITT principal and use a portfolio to document improvement).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate the importance of all components of physical fitness in achieving a desired level of health-enhancing physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in stretching to improve flexibility and cool down after physical activity.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe and apply an understanding of the concepts of health-related physical fitness to an individual exercise program.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Select and participate in an exercise program utilizing curl-ups and push-ups to improve muscular strength and endurance; develop an aerobic dance routine; and/or create and participate in five partner exercises using medicine balls.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in a personal health-related physical fitness program.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify target heart rate and sustain an aerobic activity for 20 minutes while maintaining target heart rate.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Assess fitness levels and develop a personal exercise program that will maintain or improve all fitness components.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Develop a six-week, outside of class physical activity program, based on results from a physical fitness assessment and participate in sports that will improve upper body strength.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Responsible Personal and Social Behavior: Students exhibit responsible personal and social behavior that respects self and others in physical activity settings.
Identify and demonstrate an understanding of rules and safety practices for games and other physical activities

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Exhibit successful participation in activities/games with boundary lines (e.g., cones and lines indicate activity parameters) and understand rules for safe active play (e.g., awareness of personal space).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Exhibit a willingness to follow basic directions for an active class.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Respond to teacher's signals for start and stop, verbal cues, directions, and visual demonstrations.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Show a positive attitude toward self and others during physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Exercise alone and exercise with other children in which differences exist (e.g., ability, race, gender, and socioeconomic status).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate respect for other children in physical education class.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice a skill with the person or group to which one is assigned.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and demonstrate safety practices and personal responsibility during physical education class, recess and after school physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe safety rules for participating in activities/games with boundary lines (e.g., play in the area identified with cones or lines) in which everyone is moving, and activities/games that involve objects being thrown (e.g., maintain personal space, maintain ready hands and eyes, wear tennis shoes, keep hair out of eyes).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate and apply an understanding of rules and directions for an active class.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice skills and follow rules and directions when participating in activities/games (e.g., tell what consequences will occur for continued disregard of the rules and directions: 1st- a warning, 2nd- a time out from the practice or game).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate cooperative play with children of varying abilities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate with a child of different ability (e.g., less fit, more skilled) in class activities (e.g., student and classmate cooperatively play together in an indoor soccer leadup game).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate respect and compassion for children with individual differences.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Dance with an assigned classmate; support the participation of a student with a disability in a skill development or physical fitness activity/game.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and demonstrate safety practices and personal responsibility for an active class and games.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe safety rules for participating in activities/games with boundary lines (e.g., play in the area identified with cones or lines), activities/games in which everyone is moving and that involve objects being thrown (e.g., maintain personal space, maintain ready hands and eyes, wear tennis shoes, keep hair out of eyes); notify the teacher if a student has an injury so activity can be suspended and care provided to the student.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate and apply rules and directions for an active class.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recall rules before participating in an activity/game and describe positive and negative consequences (e.g., sticker reward for following rules and directions; 1st – a warning, 2nd – a time out from class activity for disregarding rules and directions).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate cooperative play with a partner and small or large groups regardless of personal differences.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate a positive attitude for all classmates in skill development and physical fitness activities and practice positive sportsmanship (e.g., resolve conflict with honesty and respect).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate respect and compassion for students with individual differences.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate assistance and encouragement to a peer who is struggling with a skill (e.g., verbal and nonverbal language is used respectfully with peers).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Work cooperatively with others to obtain common goals in a game situation.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice the instep soccer pass with a partner while applying concepts of movement (e.g., power, direction, time) to make the passes more accurate.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize and avoid unsafe practices and situations.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Adhere to recommended safety rules and use of safety equipment while skating in physical education class, home and/or the community (e.g., wear wrist guards and elbow pads, skate under control).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate respect and compassion for the individual differences of others while participating in physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Share equipment with classmates of varying ability (lower fitness, more skill) during physical activities; choose to participate in a game or dance activity with a classmate of another gender, race, culture, or country.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Encourage classmates who demonstrate difficulty with skill performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Express encouragement to a classmate attempting to finish the one mile walk/run at a comfortable pace; help a classmate learn and practice a new skill.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Exhibit independence and the ability to succeed in groups in physical activity settings.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in cooperative and challenge activities (student designed game); participate cooperatively with friends in a self-officiated game.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Follow rules and safe practices in all class activities without being reminded.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Stop activity immediately upon signal from a student referee.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the similarities and differences between games of different countries.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Compare and contrast baseball in the United States with cricket in England.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize the various abilities and limitations of classmates and understand the adaptations they make when participating in different physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: While participating blindfolded, students work with a partner to maneuver through an obstacle course.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate the qualities of a competent and enthusiastic physical activity participant.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Accept loss with a respectful attitude; win gracefully in game situations.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform activities safely and follow rules.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe appropriate conduct including social behaviors (e.g., wear provided safety equipment, share by moving the ball around to others, take turns when there is limited equipment).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate positive attitude towards self and others during physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate a respect for peers of varying skill levels; encourage others, including those on the opposing team, by recognizing their good play.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Resolve conflict in socially acceptable ways.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss rule infraction with a classmate who does not feel he/she was fouled in the game.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Accept partners and teammates regardless of personal differences.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate acceptance of other's limitations with positive verbal and nonverbal behavior.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in cooperative activities in a leadership or followership role.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Work efficiently and successfully with classmates in a cooperative activity to reach a group goal.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Acknowledge and apply rules to game situations to ensure personal and group safety.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Refrain from using a tackling maneuver when playing flag football.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in dances and games from various world cultures.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a German Polka, Tinikling (Philippine dance), Troika (Russian dance), or Takraw (kick volleyball).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Illustrate an appreciation of the accomplishments of all group members in group or team physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a follow-up discussion after a cooperative game and express positive contributions of each group member.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Contribute to the development of and adherence to rules that provide for safe participation in physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Assist teacher with putting safety equipment (e.g., tumbling mats) where needed for physical activities and/or help develop class rules that will lead to safe participation.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Accept responsibilities of being a part of a team and strive to make contributions toward team success.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Volunteer to play various positions in a game situation including an unfamiliar or undesirable position for the good of the team.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Follow the rules of games and activities to ensure a safe environment for participants.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Refrain from running on a swimming pool deck, stay seated while in a kayak, and use safety equipment while riding a scooter or bicycle.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and participate in sports or activities that are native to a selected country.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a game of cricket in physical education class; explain the game of cricket in a speech to a social studies class.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Adapt games to allow the participation of individuals of varying abilities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a game that requires each member to touch the ball before it can be shot at the goal.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in cooperative games that require a contribution from all team members.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a parachute volleyball activity and/or a cooperative game of choice.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Develop leadership and followership skills and personal choice in physical activity settings.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Volunteer for class leadership opportunities (e.g., lead warm-up fitness activity).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform safely and follow class rules of conduct and game rules.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Play floor hockey with no stick checking (i.e., blocking an opponent with the hockey stick) and respect the safety of other participants.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognize and correct unsafe situations related to participation in physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Examine the area to identify any potential hazards prior to playing; use a helmet when biking or skateboarding; and/or swim only in areas determined to be safe and guarded by a certified lifeguard.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate a positive attitude toward self and peers through physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Win and lose gracefully when participating in all physical activities and/or encourage teammates.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Value others during physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Seek out, participate with, and show respect for persons of various skill levels.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Resolve conflicts and accept decisions or judgments in socially acceptable ways.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Accept and respect the decisions of teacher or student officials.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Value of Physical Activity: Students value physical activity for health, enjoyment, challenge, self- expression, and/or social interaction.
Express enjoyment and self-confidence when participating in movement experiences.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate active participation in a child-centered lesson for learning new skills (e.g., teacher plans developmentally appropriate lessons to minimize the effect of initial failures: physical fitness activities/games that do not eliminate students, use of balloons for striking with a racquet or paddle, use lightweight balls for bouncing).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Discuss personal opinions about participation in physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Express verbal feedback of an activity to the teacher (e.g., teacher evaluates a lesson by informally asking students their opinion of a game/activity and observes if participation was active or passive).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Acquire new skills and demonstrate a determination to develop those skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate active engagement in the physical education lesson; student actively participates with little or no prompting from the teacher.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify personal goals and demonstrate a willingness to achieve specific movement skills and physical fitness challenges.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify goals, with teacher guidance, and practice to improve and achieve goals (e.g., land on feet for cartwheel improvement and success; overhand throw to hit the target from a 10 foot distance for overhand throw success; reach or exceed a personal goal one can walk/run laps in 10 minutes for cardio-respiratory improvement and success).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Respond to and apply basic skill elements, given by the teacher, for learning and developing motor skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate skill acquisition and/or improvement when striking with a racquet (e.g., keep wrist firm on the racquet handle, put two hands on the handle, watch the balloon/ball, move feet).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate self-expression in a physical activity setting.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Show creativity in a partner Follow the Leader game with bouncing (dribbling) a ball (e.g., one student, as a leader, creates a ball bouncing sequence as a classmate follows).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Express enthusiasm for participating in physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Express excitement for physical education class with verbal and nonverbal communication about skill development activities and/or physical fitness activities/games (e.g., the teacher uses conversation from students and observation of students to evaluate a lesson).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify personal goals and demonstrate a willingness to achieve specific movement skills and physical fitness challenges.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Identify goals to achieve, self determined and/or teacher determined, and practice to improve skills (e.g., jump rope skills for improvement and success: turning the rope backwards, skier jump, side straddle jump; 15 or more bump-ups with a racquet or a paddle for eye-hand coordination improvement and success; reach or exceed the personal goal one can walk/run laps in 10 minutes for cardio-respiratory improvement and success).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Respond to and apply basic skill elements, given by the teacher, for learning and developing motor skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate skill improvement and/or acquisition when striking a beach ball and progressing to a trainer volleyball (e.g., various sizes: medium and large; light weight and oversized) with forearms/bumping (e.g., hands together, arms straight, watch the ball, move feet, arms meet the ball gently).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Express enthusiasm as a result of participation in physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Express excitement for physical education class with verbal and nonverbal communication after participation in skill development activities and/or physical fitness activities/games (e.g., the teacher uses conversation from students and observation of students to evaluate a lesson); willingly self evaluates specific motor skill or physical fitness improvement (e.g., the teacher designs an age appropriate checklist for student self evaluation).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate feelings through a pattern of locomotor and nonlocomotor movements.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Create a dance that expresses a variety of emotions (e.g., happiness, sadness, excitement, calmness).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Express enjoyment when applying new skills while participating in partner and group physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Choose to do an activity at recess with a friend rather than by self; move with a partner over, under, and through an obstacle course while helping each other as needed.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in cooperative problem-solving physical activity challenges.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in a cooperative education initiative, with a small group of students, in an attempt to move from one side of the activity area to the other using a variety of equipment (e.g., long boards, scooters, carpet squares).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in physical activities that are enjoyable.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate on the school's demonstration/after school team for jumping rope; record physical activity participation during recess and after school in student activity portfolio.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Interact positively with classmates and friends in physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Cooperatively participate in physical activity with friends during physical education class and after school play sessions.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in new and challenging physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Traverse the low elements on an adventure education initiative (e.g., balance beam, spider web) in physical education class; learn a new physical activity or sport.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Exhibit positive feelings about participation in physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Celebrate individual success and group accomplishment following the completion of a challenging jump rope routine to music.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Engage in the challenge of new activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Develop skills to participate in new games, sports, or rhythmic activities.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Engage in and enjoy independent and interactive physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Incorporate physical activities with friends and family during leisure time; use fitness-based video games at home; record activity, time, intensity, and social experience in a chart and/or notebook.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Use physical activity as a means of self-expression.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Create and perform a movement sequence with a small group that dramatizes a chapter from a book read in language arts class.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Engage in physical activities as an opportunity to socialize with friends and family.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in an impromptu game of touch football with neighborhood friends.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in challenging activities requiring the utilization of newly acquired skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Join a family member or friend in tennis, orienteering, or canoeing.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify the social, emotional, and physical benefits of participation in physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Write a paragraph, create a power point, or videotape a testimonial about how it feels to successfully master a new physical skill; identify the skills learned from participating in a new physical activity; and/or describe games or sports that can provide opportunities for individuals of all skill levels to participate.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrate movement patterns that convey various emotions.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Create a modern dance that shows a feeling of exuberance; run a pass pattern with intensity.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in challenge and adventure activities that require the development of strategies and teamwork.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Design and participate in a human obstacle course or personal circuit training program.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and practice a physical activity/exercise or movement that is difficult to perform in order to increase skill/fitness level.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Utilize the freestyle stroke in swimming while concentrating on flutter kicking and rhythmic breathing; use the pass, set, hit sequence in volleyball.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Exhibit winning and losing gracefully within the physical activity context.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe ways to use body and movement activities to communicate ideas and feelings (e.g., spike a volleyball with force and intensity; win and lose gracefully) in a safe and positive manner.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Engage in challenging new physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Select, receive instruction, and participate in a new activity (e.g., climbing wall, ropes course, martial arts).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Engage in independent and interactive physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate with a group of friends on a bicycle ride, canoe outing, hiking excursion, or in a pick-up game of basketball at a neighborhood park.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: High School Level 1
Reading for Literacy in PE

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The following standards offer a focus for instruction each year and help ensure that students gain adequate exposure to a range of texts and tasks. Rigor is also infused through the requirement that students read increasingly complex texts through the grades. Students advancing through the grades are expected to meet each year's grade-specific standards and retain or further develop skills and understandings mastered in preceding grades.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Key Ideas and Details
Cite specific textual evidence to support analysis of technical texts, attending to the precise details of explanations or descriptions (This standard not required in PE).

Determine the central ideas or conclusions of a text; trace the text's explanation or depiction of a complex process, phenomenon, concept; provide an accurate summary of the text (This standard not required in PE).
Follow precisely a complex multistep procedure when performing technical tasks, attending to special cases or exceptions defined in the text (This standard not required in PE).
Craft and Structure
Determine the meaning of symbols, key terms, and other domain-specific words and phrases as they are used in a specific technical physical education context relevant to grades 9-12 texts and topics.
Analyze the structure of the relationships among concepts in a text, including relationships among key terms (e.g., force, friction, distance, object).

Analyze the author's purpose in providing an explanation, describing a procedure, or discussing an experiment in a text, defining the question the author seeks to address (This standard not required in PE).
Integration of Knowledge and Ideas

Translate technical PE information expressed in words in a text into visual form (e.g., a table, chart, court and field diagrams) and translate information expressed visually or mechanically (e.g., in an equation) into words.
Assess the extent to which the reasoning and evidence in a text support the author's claim or a recommendation for solving a technical problem (This standard not required in PE).

Compare and contrast findings presented in a text to those from other sources (including their own experiments), noting when the findings support or contradict previous explanations or accounts (This standard not required in PE).
