Motor Skills and Movement Patterns: Students demonstrate competency in motor skills and movement patterns needed to perform a variety of physical activities.
Demonstrate activity-specific skills in individual, dual, and team physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in tactical games that require advanced eye-hand/foot coordination and high levels of strategy (e.g., net/wall, field, invasion, and target sports using specialized skills and strategies).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform creative rhythmic movement patterns with increasing degrees of difficulty.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Choreograph and perform movement sequences and/or dances to a musical selection.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Model or teach mature motor skills and movement patterns to another student.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Instruct a peer how to perform a proficient badminton serve.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform specific skills at an advanced performance level.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Practice tennis strokes by successfully executing a forehand drive, backhand drive, serve, lob, and/or overhead smash.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Movement Concepts: Students demonstrate an understanding of movement concepts, principles, strategies, and tactics as they apply to the learning and performance of physical activities.
Apply previously learned strategies and tactics in the performance of selected physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate in physical activities (e.g., martial arts, table tennis, team handball) using appropriate tactical decisions (a plan of action to advance a purpose or gain an advantage).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze and evaluate information about motor skills and patterns that lead to improved physical performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Analyze and judge the effects of force, motion, and stability (balance) on successful physical performance (e.g., videotape a golf swing and identify the critical elements of the skill).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Physical Activity: Students participate regularly in physical activity.
Identify available community resources that promote an active lifestyle.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Construct a list of local facilities that offer fitness activities, calculate the cost of participating, and participate in at least one of these activities (e.g., inquire with a community center about the cost of attending a yoga or aerobics class).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Compare and contrast available community and/or online resources that provide active lifestyle products for purchase.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Compare prices of running shoes from a variety of venues and make an informed consumer choice for the purchase.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate in physical activities that contribute to the improvement of specific health-related physical fitness components (cardiorespiratory endurance, muscular strength, muscular endurance, flexibility, and body composition).

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform selected physical activities that enhance flexibility (e.g., stretching, stretch bands, partner stretching, resistance exercises through the full range of motion).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate regularly in lifetime physical activities, with consideration of frequency, duration, and intensity, that contribute to improved physical fitness and wellness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Run, walk, or bicycle for an accumulated 60 minutes per day six days per week to achieve an age-specific and gender-specific exercise heart rate.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Health-Enhancing Physical Fitness: Students achieve and maintain a health-enhancing level of physical fitness.
Create a personal workout program to achieve and maintain an optimal level of health-related physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Design, implement, and monitor a personal fitness program based upon the results of a pretest, frequent self-assessment, indicators of success, and personal goals (e.g., set a bench press lifting goal based on a pretest and gradually increase weight and repetitions).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and evaluate personal physiological responses to exercise.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Monitor body responses before, during, and after exercise by checking and recording measurements for heart rate, exertion, and recovery time (e.g., use heart rate monitor to measure body response to exercise).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify basic principles of exercise, nutrition, and chemical substances and their effects on physical performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Investigate the prevalence of performance enhancing drugs (artificial means to improve physical abilities) on athletes and summarize the harmful impact to the individual and society; create a power point of the harmful effects to present to a class.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Responsible Personal and Social Behavior: Students exhibit responsible personal and social behavior that respects self and others in physical activity settings.
Demonstrate safe and appropriate use and care of equipment and facilities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Anticipate potentially dangerous situations related to physical activity (e.g., attach safety clip to shirt while operating the treadmill; check a softball bat prior to stepping up to the plate).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Relate the benefits of physical activities to social and emotional well-being.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Participate with friends and/or family in physical activities to relax, relieve stress.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the potential physiological risks associated with physical activity in various environments.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Track environmental conditions to avoid dehydration, overexertion, heat exhaustion, and hypothermia during physical activity (e.g., monitor temperature and humidity; drink water while jogging and/or playing tennis or football in hot weather; wear sunscreen; identify sheltered areas for protection in hot or cold environments).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify how age, gender, ethnicity, and economic status affect physical activity selection, participation, and personal abilities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Compare similarities and differences in cross-cultural games (e.g., research differences between lacrosse and stickball, netball and basketball, and rugby and football) in relation to participation possibilities in different countries.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Develop strategies for inclusion of all students in physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Discuss and implement how activities, games, and equipment can be adapted to meet the needs of everyone including individuals with disabilities (e.g., develop swimming strategies to include a student with cerebral palsy).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Apply game rules accurately and fairly during activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Self-officiate a game of pickleball with a classmate in an agreeable manner.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Value of Physical Activity: Students value physical activity for health, enjoyment, challenge, self- expression, and/or social interaction.
Identify positive mental and emotional aspects of participation in a variety of physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Describe the psychological benefits of swimming laps with family members two times a week (e.g., mental alertness, relaxation, social interaction).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Express feelings of satisfaction and enjoyment as a result of participating in regular physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Express emotions and release energy and/or stress by participating in a challenging game of tennis.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Reflect on reasons for choosing to participate in selected physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Create and distribute a pamphlet to promote the health benefits of physical activity for peers.

Motor Skills and Movement Patterns: Students demonstrate competency in motor skills and movement patterns needed to perform a variety of physical activities.
Perform and analyze activity-specific skills in individual, dual, and team physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Demonstrate and analyze a sport skill for maximum effectiveness and efficiency (e.g., determine the best technique for performing the power clean in weight lifting).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Synthesize and perform creative rhythmic movement patterns with increasing degrees of difficulty.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Choreograph and perform movement sequences and/or dances in a public venue.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Model or teach mature motor skills and movement patterns to other students.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Peer instruct several students how to serve a volleyball proficiently.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Perform specific skills at a difficult performance level.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Rescue a drowning victim, in a simulated situation, using proper lifeguard procedures; run a 5K race after training for six weeks; play in a 3 on 3 basketball tournament with friends.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Movement Concepts: Students demonstrate an understanding of movement concepts, principles, strategies, and tactics as they apply to the learning and performance of physical activities.
Apply previously learned strategies and tactics to advanced physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Develop and execute appropriate game strategies to offset the opponent's strategies in a game of badminton.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze and evaluate information about complex motor skills that lead to improved physical performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Design a plan for improved performance after analyzing the biomechanical principles of several sport skills (e.g., view a DVD of an intermediate swimmer performing the butterfly stroke, analyze, and recommend skill component corrections for stroke improvement) and explain how that performance maximizes those principles.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Physical Activity: Students participate regularly in physical activity.
Compare and contrast available community resources that promote an active lifestyle and select an activity in which to participate.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Calculate the costs/benefits of joining a local fitness facility (e.g., document monetary cost, services provided, and value of fitness centers in the community).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Summarize available community and/or online resources that provide active lifestyle products and services for purchase.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Recommend the best vendor from which to purchase the equipment needed to participate in a chosen physical activity after creating a chart that lists the pricing and vendors.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe and demonstrate physical activities that contribute to the improvement of specific fitness components (cardiorespiratory endurance, muscular strength, muscular endurance, flexibility, and body composition).

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Explain and perform an activity that will achieve the specific fitness components (e.g., write and produce a two minute video identifying a specific muscle group and acting out some exercises that can be used to strengthen that set of muscles to show during the weekly school television announcements).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participate regularly in lifetime physical activities (minimum accumulated total of 60 minutes of moderate intensity activity most days of the week) that contribute to improved physical fitness and wellness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Perform and document the recommended number of minutes of moderate to vigorous physical activity outside of physical education class on six days during the week.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Health-Enhancing Physical Fitness: Students achieve and maintain a health-enhancing level of physical fitness.
Design and implement a personal workout program to achieve and maintain an optimal level of health-related physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Formulate and modify a six week fitness program or sport activity for self, family member, or friend who wants to get in better physical condition.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify and evaluate personal physiological responses to exercise.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Record the frequency, intensity, and duration of an exercise program and interpret the data over time; strategize ways to overcome difficulties with and barriers to exercising regularly (e.g., explain how varying intensity of workouts is important in building strong muscles).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Compare and contrast basic principles of exercise, nutrition, and chemical substances and their effects on the physical performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Evaluate nutritional choices and steroid use and their impact on physical performance.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Responsible Personal and Social Behavior: Students exhibit responsible personal and social behavior that respects self and others in physical activity settings.
Demonstrate safe and appropriate use and care of equipment and facilities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Coordinate pool safety checks as a component of a lifeguarding class.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Advocate for the benefits of physical activities on social and emotional health.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Present benefits of physical education on social and emotional well-being at a school board meeting (e.g., a group presentation relating personal experiences, present results of improved fitness and healthy weight control on self confidence of students); create and distribute a brochure on the benefits of physical activity on health and wellness.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Assess the potential physiological risks associated with physical activity in various environments.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Consider the effects of humid weather on a person with a respiratory condition and adapt the physical activity if necessary (e.g., small groups of students give an interactive digital presentation showing current research on asthma and its effects on exercise).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine how age, gender, ethnicity, and economic status affect physical activity selection, participation, and personal abilities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Predict how health and physical activity are impacted by aging or examine the physical activity participation habits of males and females.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Develop a personal philosophy and practice that reflect inclusive practices of physical activity and sport participation.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Volunteer for a health-related/special needs physical activity event in the community.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Apply game rules accurately and fairly during physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Officiate an intramural, youth and/or community physical activity contest.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Value of Physical Activity: Students value physical activity for health, enjoyment, challenge, self- expression, and/or social interaction.
Promote positive mental and emotional aspects of participation in a variety of physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Advocate for opportunities to participate in physical activities before and/or after the school day as a way to keep students connected to positive role models and peers (e.g., intramurals, open gym, advanced physical education classes).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Appraise feelings of satisfaction and enjoyment as a result of participating in regular physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Reflect on accomplishment and reward self after achieving a physical activity goal.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Reflect on reasons for choosing to participate in lifetime physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Example: Dialogue with classmates as to the benefits of swimming versus cycling as available individual lifetime pursuits and/or create a commercial to videotape.
